{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509904"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:21:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:21:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11454"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11454"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.16,0.54,0.17,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4088"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97340"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4088"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11454"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79938"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4814"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5608"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11272"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16600"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33322"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97340"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after being found confused on the street. He has a history of hypercholesterolaemia, hypertension, and a right middle cerebral artery infarct three months ago. His medications include atorvastatin, ramipril, and aspirin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is confused, with a pulse rate of 88/min, blood pressure 148/80 mmHg, and SpO2 98% on room air. There is urine on his pants. Neurological examination shows confusion and some residual left-sided weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT brain shows gliosis in the right parietal region and bilateral atrophy of the temporal and hippocampal regions. While in the department, he has a witnessed episode of sudden jerking of all limbs, urinary incontinence, and tongue-biting.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Traumatic brain injury","Alzheimer\u0027s disease","Previous stroke","Brain tumour","Bacterial meningitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with a seizure and post-ictal confusion. The most likely underlying cause is his \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevious stroke\u003C/strong\u003E. Cerebrovascular events are the leading cause of both acute symptomatic seizures and epilepsy in the elderly. It is estimated that 20-50% of epilepsy in the elderly is secondary to prior strokes, and about 10% of patients with stroke develop seizures within the next five years. The gliosis in the right parietal lobe, as seen on the CT scan, is likely the source of seizure activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlzheimer\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause seizures, but it is less likely in this case given the recent stroke and the CT findings. While the CT scan shows bilateral atrophy of the temporal and hippocampal regions, which can be seen in Alzheimer\u0027s, the recent stroke is a more immediate and likely cause of the seizure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETraumatic brain injury\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for a smaller percentage of epilepsy in the elderly. There is no history of recent head trauma, and the lack of other symptoms such as headaches or visual disturbances makes this less likely to be the cause of the seizure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrain tumours\u003C/strong\u003E can cause seizures, but there are no focal neurological deficits or other symptoms suggestive of a brain tumour in this patient. The CT scan did not reveal any mass lesions, making this an unlikely cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial meningitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an important cause of seizures to consider, but the patient lacks other typical features of meningitis such as fever, neck stiffness, or recent infective symptoms. The absence of these makes bacterial meningitis an unlikely cause of his presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, given the patient\u0027s history of recent stroke, the CT findings of right parietal gliosis, and the absence of other clear causes, the previous stroke is the most likely underlying cause of this patient\u0027s seizure. The post-ictal confusion, urinary incontinence, and tongue-biting are typical features following a generalized tonic-clonic seizure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Previous cerebrovascular disease is the most common known cause of symptomatic epilepsy in the elderly.","Seizures can occur months to years after a stroke, with 10% of stroke patients developing seizures within five years.","Post-ictal confusion and urinary incontinence are common features following a generalized tonic-clonic seizure."],"references":["Acharya JN, Acharya VJ. Epilepsy in the elderly: special considerations and challenges. Annals of Indian Academy of Neurology. 2014 Mar;17(Suppl 1):S18. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24791083/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79938"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11454"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79938"